Good [first] post. As an addendum to that post, another misinterpretation by non-EQ'ers is that EQ completely dominates <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> every</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> aspect of our lives by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> replacing</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> other forms of interaction and entertainment.<br>
<br>
There is the automatic presumption that EQ <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> must</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> replace other forms of social interaction rather than sitting quite nicely alongside them. I myself work, have a full and varied social life, have various hubs and networks of friends, a range of other pursuits and interests of which, EQ is but one. <br>
<br>
Now I may spend x hours on EQ compared to y activity, but EQ is not at the expense or exclusion of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> all</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of my other activities. However, EQ or any other related phenomena is a convenient scapegoat, especially when backed up with pseudo-scientific evidence to lay all manner of social evils at its door.<br>
<br>
