<br>
Pretend that tomorrow all the people who may have tried to get your attention while you play EQ are gone. Would you have acted differently?<br>
<br>
In many cases I would wager that people play EQ as a buffer from these real life encounters...an excuse if you will for not having to deal with the day to day crap we're all forced to stomach.<br>
<br>
Now you can make the argument that anything we do can be held up to the same standard -- from going to a movie, to watching TV, to going for a walk, to even going to work or school. However, the main difference is that to be &quot;successful&quot; in EQ requires large chunks of dedicated time. You are effectively penalized if your play style is short times of play as you need time to get people together, get to a target, clear to it etc. <br>
<br>
If you want to go see a movie or do something else, you just pick the activity and go. It may take 3 hours from start to finish or more, but you're not facing severe situational penalties for changing your plans or having to deal with other people's needs. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uhalochanter.showPublicProfile?language=EN>HaloChanter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Local Resident</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/9/02 5:57:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=787.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: *yawns* I present the ever-repeated debate..[Long]</span><hr size=1> CaeanthePaladin.. I am forced to agree.<br>
